<!-- ZEQ.=6,SEQ=77,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=729314,FOLIO='72',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DS75001A.;18',USER='GNEWBUR',CD='28-JUL-2016;18:38' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DS75001_1_73">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Training and development
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We grow and develop talent through a combination of professional training and mentorship programs involving senior technology
	specialists and industry experts. Each new hire is exposed to a training curriculum that covers methodology and industry standards, technologies and tools, management and communication skills,
	software engineering processes, and domain knowledge.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally,
	our three training centers in Russia, three in Ukraine, one in Romania, one in Bulgaria, two in Poland, one in the U.K., and one in Vietnam conduct more than 1,500 training
	courses per year and host over 8,800 specialists (including our personnel and external students) for general training courses and client-specific education programs. We typically conduct between 78
	and 172 resident training sessions per month with an average of 12 students per group, and fulfill nearly 900&nbsp;additional training requests per month via our e-learning system. Additionally,
	during the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 we completed 3,025 four-month foreign language training requests for English, Polish, Bulgarian, and Romanian as well as 34 closed foreign training
	requests using our e-learning tool that are comprised of 10 12-month-long licenses. Our training program delivers different professional competencies; including disciplines rarely covered by
	university curriculums, such as system analysis, system architecture and project management.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Each
	new hire is placed on a probation period for up to six months. During this time, new hires become part of a mentoring, monitoring, coaching and motivational program. Each IT
	professional is assigned to a People Manager, who is responsible for project evaluation, performance appraisal and planning of professional development of the new hire. Additionally, each IT
	professional undergoes a
	performance appraisal session at least once a year to measure technical performance, teamwork skills and possession of the core competencies required for his or her respective role within the Company.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Recruitment and retention
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe our Company's culture and reputation, along with the talent in the regions in which we operate, enhances our ability to
	recruit and retain sought after IT professionals. As of March&nbsp;31, 2016, we had a dedicated human resources staff of 530 people including 264 recruiters and researchers. We have compiled a
	database of over 428,000 IT specialists who have experience and specific skills relevant to our business. Our database, along with our referral program, has accounted for 40% of all new hires in the
	fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016. During the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, we hired on average 272 IT professionals each month.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	candidates come from a variety of sources, including external referrals, our regional network, our internal database and public sources. As of March&nbsp;31, 2016, approximately
	76% of our personnel had more than five years of industry experience and approximately 79% of our personnel hold Master's degrees (or Master's degree equivalents) or higher.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	order to keep our attrition rate low, we focus on retaining our personnel through mandatory monthly evaluation reports, an employee rotation program and a targeted approach to enable
	different career opportunities within the Company. We motivate and promote key personnel through our High Performers Club, which identifies personnel with strong management potential and offers them
	additional training as well as direct interaction with top management. We also offer executive training programs, corporate MBA programs and executive leadership programs at top schools including the
	University of Pennsylvania, Harvard University, Stanford University and Massachusetts Institute of Technology, in which several of our top managers have already participated.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Competition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The markets in which we compete are changing rapidly and we face competition from global and Asia-based IT services providers as well
	as local providers based in CEE. We believe that the principal
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	73
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=7,SEQ=78,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=601181,FOLIO='73',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DS75001A.;18',USER='GNEWBUR',CD='28-JUL-2016;18:38' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DS75001_1_74">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	competitive
	factors in our business include breadth and depth of service offerings, technical expertise and industry knowledge, reputation and track record for high-quality and on-time delivery of
	work, effective personnel recruiting, training and retention, responsiveness to clients' business needs, ability to scale, financial stability and price. Our industry is split between low-cost vendors
	that provide inexpensive, commoditized services and high-cost vendors that provide specialized and complex services at a premium cost. Our ability to provide complex, customized services at
	competitive cost has positioned us between these two classes of vendors.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	face competition primarily from:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	IT outsourcing service providers in India, such as Cognizant Technology and Infosys;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Global multinational consulting and outsourcing firms such as Accenture, Capgemini and CSC;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Local CEE technology outsourcing IT service providers such as EPAM; and
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In-house IT departments of our clients and potential clients.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Although
	we do not often compete for engagements with providers in Brazil, China, Israel or Mexico, we may experience competition from vendors in these countries in the future. We
	believe that we have a strong competitive position in the market for complex software outsourcing and custom application development based on third-party industry rankings and client feedback. We
	believe our focus on complex software product development services, our skilled technical personnel base and continuous improvement of process methodologies, applications and platforms positions us to
	compete effectively
	in the future. Furthermore, we believe that the barriers to entry into our niche segment are relatively high, as new entrants must secure substantial amounts of financial and high-quality human
	resources to provide adequate services, flexibility and scale to compete for a comparable client base. See "ITEM 3. Key Information&#151;D. Risk Factors&#151;Risks related to our
	business and our industry&#151;We operate in a highly competitive environment and may not be able to compete successfully."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Intellectual property rights
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We rely on a combination of intellectual property laws, trade secrets, confidentiality procedures and contractual provisions to protect
	our intellectual property. In addition, our intellectual property is protected under a number of international conventions. Russia, Ukraine, Romania, Poland and the United States are participants to
	the Berne Convention for the Protection of Literary Artistic Works and the Stockholm Convention establishing the World Intellectual Property Organization. Russia, Ukraine and the United States
	participate in the Universal Copyright Convention adopted under the Geneva Convention; and the United States, Ukraine and Romania participate in WTO agreements including the Agreement on Trade-Related
	Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights and ITA. We also rely on local civil legislation to protect our intellectual property rights.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	customarily enter into master services agreements or general framework agreements with our clients that include terms for the transfer and use by our clients of intellectual property
	created by us. All intellectual property rights created by our employees and contractors are transferred to us subject to local laws and regulations and terms of agreements entered into with such
	employees and contractors. Most of our software development services are specifically ordered and custom-built for the client, and therefore all intellectual property rights created by our employees
	and contractors are transferred to the client at the time of delivery. Furthermore, our agreements with clients typically contain provisions that allow us to grant a perpetual, worldwide,
	royalty-free, non-exclusive, transferable and non-revocable license to our clients to use our own intellectual property, but only to the extent necessary in order to use the software or systems we
	developed for them. Historically, we have rarely relied on and granted licenses under these provisions, but may do so in the future as we seek to commercialize our solutions. Sometimes the
	intellectual property rights for some of our software are
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	74
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	not
	registered, which may expose us to intellectual property risks if we rely on these provisions to grant rights to our unregistered software in the future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If
	requested by clients, we may incorporate third-party software into our software development for clients. In these cases, we acquire all necessary licenses for such software once we
	reach a preliminary agreement with clients. Intellectual property rights for such third-party software are always subject to separate license agreements with third parties. We are in the process of
	developing our own intellectual property rights for products which we are planning to sell to end users based on license agreements with end users. For example, we have acquired intellectual property
	rights for the Horizon software from one of our financial services clients and we have been licensing the same to some of our clients. See "ITEM 3. Key Information&#151;D. Risk
	Factors&#151;Risks related to our business and our industry&#151;We may be subject to third-party claims of intellectual property infringement that could be time-consuming and costly to
	defend."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">

	regulations, and several government agencies in the United States and abroad, especially in CEE countries, regulate various aspects of our business. See the following risk factors in "ITEM 3. Key
	Information&#151;D. Risk Factors" for more information on regulation material to our business, financial condition and results of operations:

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>

<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->

</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our business is moderately seasonal and our results of operations vary from quarter to quarter based in part upon the budget and work
	cycles of our clients. Our operating results are typically lower in the first fiscal quarter of each year due to increases in wages and other costs that typically occur in the beginning of each fiscal
	year. For more information, see "ITEM 5. Operating and Financial Review and Prospects&#151;A. Operating Results&#151;Quarterly results of operations and seasonality."

<!-- ZEQ.=10,SEQ=81,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=679242,FOLIO='76',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DS75001A.;18',USER='GNEWBUR',CD='28-JUL-2016;18:38' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DS75001_1_77">

</A>
	D.&nbsp;&nbsp;Property, Plants and Equipment

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Facilities
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We currently occupy 33 offices across seventeen countries, totaling 109,220 square meters of office space. As of March&nbsp;31, 2016
	we had the capacity for 12,607 workplaces, which leaves us with a 29.57% reserve for growth. We lease all of our facilities except for one building in Romania, which we acquired as part of our
	acquisition of ITC Networks in 2008.
</FONT>

<EFX_OPERATING_AND_FINANCIAL_REVIEW>
<A NAME="FIS_OPERATING_AND_FINANCIAL_REVIEW"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_DU75001_ITEM_5__OPERATING_AND_FINANCIAL_REVIEW_AND_PROSPECTS">
</A>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_TOC_DU75001_1">
</A>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	ITEM 5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating and Financial Review and Prospects
<BR>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You should read the following discussion and analysis of our financial condition and results of operations in conjunction with the
	section titled "ITEM 3. Key Information&#151;A. Selected Financial Data" and the consolidated financial statements included elsewhere in this report. This discussion and analysis may contain
	forward-looking statements within the meaning of the U.S. Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995. The words "believes," "anticipates," "plans," "expects," and similar expressions are
	intended to identify forward-looking statements. Our actual results may differ materially from those anticipated in the forward-looking statements made herein as a result of various risks,
	uncertainties and other important factors, including those set forth in "ITEM 3. Key Information&#151;D. Risk Factors" of this annual report. Any such forward-looking statements represent
	management's estimates as of the date of this annual report. While we may elect to update such forward-looking statements at some point in the future, we disclaim any obligation to do so, even if
	subsequent events cause our views to change. These forward-looking statements should not be relied upon as representing our views as of any date
	subsequent to the date of this annual report. Our financial statements have been prepared in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_DU_5A">
</A>
	A.&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating Results
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Factors affecting our results of operations
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe the following factors have had and may continue to have a significant effect on our results of
	operations:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Wage inflation:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Wage inflation has been growing rapidly
	in the countries in which we maintain a significant number of personnel. Wage inflation contributes to increases in our cost of services, and selling, general and administrative expenses. The impact
	of wage inflation is heightened by increased attrition, which is caused by the increasing demand for qualified IT personnel. The impact of wage inflation is mitigated to a limited extent by several
	factors, including our ability to shift work away from delivery centers that may be disproportionately affected by wage inflation, as well as our ability to pass some of the cost to our clients
	through provisions in a number of our contracts that permit us to increase prices based on inflation and related indicators.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Demand for IT services outsourcing in the United States and Western
	Europe:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;The demand for IT services outsourcing is growing steadily in the United States and Western Europe, the regions in which most of
	our clients operate. The growth in demand for IT services outsourcing in key regions in which we operate gives us the ability to increase our sales of services and, therefore, may positively impact
	our results of operations. Conversely, if the growth in demand for IT services outsourcing slows or declines, our revenues may be negatively impacted. We focus on providing services primarily to
	mission critical aspects of our clients' businesses, which we believe reduces the risk of our clients decreasing their IT spending on our engagements during economic downturns relative to those IT
	services providers who focus on discretionary projects and business process outsourcing.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Client concentration
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	: In the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, 68.6% of our
	sales were derived from clients in the financial services industry. We believe we will continue to have similar levels of revenue concentration in the financial services industry in the near term. The
	developments in this industry that impact the demand for software development services and solutions are likely to have a greater impact on us than on competitors, who do not have a similarly high
	level of revenue concentration in this vertical. Furthermore, we have a high degree of client concentration and our top five clients represented an aggregate of 64.9% of our sales in the fiscal year
	ended March&nbsp;31, 2016. We believe that the financial services industry will remain one of the most significant sources of demand for IT services in the near term, driven by ongoing
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	79
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=84,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=548294,FOLIO='79',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DU75001A.;12',USER='MORAM',CD='26-JUL-2016;19:07' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DU75001_1_80">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	pressure
	to restore growth and improve profitability, industry-wide regulatory reforms, requirements to increase transparency and manage risk exposure, as well as the adoption of new technologies such
	as cloud computing, mobile and data analytics. We believe that the financial industry's strong reliance on IT outsourcing services and the mission critical nature of the services we provide for key
	clients within the financial industry, should reduce the risks we face from client concentration.
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Foreign currency fluctuation:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;We operate in a
	multi-currency environment, and exchange rate fluctuations, especially between the U.S. dollar and the euro and currencies pegged to the euro, impact our results of operations. Our sales are largely
	denominated in U.S. dollars and euros, and, to a lesser extent, in British pounds and Russian rubles, whereas our expenses are largely denominated in U.S. dollars, Russian rubles, Polish
	z&#322;oty, British pounds and Romanian leu. As a result, currency fluctuations, especially the appreciation of the Russian ruble relative to the U.S. dollar and the depreciation of the
	euro and British pound relative to U.S. dollar, could negatively impact our results of operations. Currency exchange rates in the British pound and the euro with respect to each other and the U.S.
	dollar have been affected by the June&nbsp;23, 2016 referendum in the United Kingdom, pursuant to which the people of the United Kingdom voted for the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European
	Union ("Brexit"). As a significant portion of our revenues are derived from sales to clients located in the United Kingdom and due to our operations in the United Kingdom and Europe, further exchange
	rate fluctuations as a result of Brexit could adversely affect our business and our results of operations. See "ITEM&nbsp;3. Key Information&#151;D. Risk Factors&#151;"The vote by the
	UK electorate in favor of the United Kingdom's exit from the European Union could materially adversely affect our business and results of operations."
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Inflation in CEE:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Our results of operations are affected
	by inflation rates in CEE because our expenses are largely denominated in Russian rubles and other CEE currencies, such as Romanian leu and Polish z&#322;oty. If we are unable to increase
	our revenues in line with our costs in CEE, it could have a material effect upon our results of operations and financial condition. See "ITEM 3. Key Information&#151;D. Risk
	Factors&#151;Risks related to our business and our industry&#151;Fluctuations in currency exchange rates and increased inflation could materially adversely affect our financial condition
	and results of operations."
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Tax reduction programs:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;We benefit from tax reduction
	programs in Russia, Vietnam and Poland.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In Russia, we benefit from a reduced social contributions tax rate program available to qualified IT service providers
	complying with certain conditions set out in the Russian law. Russia's social contributions tax is a mandatory tax consisting of contributions paid by employers to the Russian Pension Fund, the
	Russian Social Security Fund and the Federal Medical Insurance Fund. The social contributions tax rate varies depending on the employer's beneficial status and the status of a particular employee
	(such as a foreign citizen or Russian citizen). Under the program, the applicable aggregate tax rate is currently reduced from the maximum of 30% to 14%. However, the reduced tax rates for social
	contributions payable by qualified IT service providers are only available until December&nbsp;31, 2017, after which it is expected that the social contributions tax rates will gradually increase to
	21.0% in the aggregate in 2018 and 28.0% in the aggregate in 2019, until becoming equal with the rates for non-qualified companies in 2020.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In Vietnam, as a resident of a high-tech zone, Quang Trung software park, we were granted full exemption from corporate
	income tax for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, and 50% reduction of corporate income tax rate for the period of 9&nbsp;years as of April&nbsp;1, 2015.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our subsidiary in Poland conducts a part of its operational activities in the territory of Wroclaw Park. Our profit
	generated from operations in the Park is non-taxable within the
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	80
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=85,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=810869,FOLIO='80',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DU75001A.;12',USER='MORAM',CD='26-JUL-2016;19:07' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DU75001_1_81">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	amount
	of tax credit calculated based on eligible expenses. Since the amount of the eligible expenses and relevant tax credit currently exceeds the amount of the income before tax payable with respect
	to profit earned in the Park, we pay no income tax in relation to this subsidiary's operations in the Park.
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Government grants:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;During the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2016, we participated in government grants programs in Romania, Poland and Bulgaria. The programs require certain investments regarding creating new workplaces and maintaining them
	during certain periods of up to five years. As a result of fulfilling the programs' requirements, we received three government grants in the total amount of $2.9&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Corporate income tax increase as a result of
	acquisitions:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;In the fiscal years ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2016, we completed three acquisitions of companies in the United
	Kingdom, United States and Germany, which resulted in an increase in our effective tax rate in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	we continue to grow our business, we plan to introduce new products for resale and licensing. We have limited experience to date in developing products for resale and licensing, and
	have not generated significant revenues from the sale of products. We expect the development of new products to increase our R&amp;D costs in the near and medium term. However, we intend to grow our
	revenues in the medium and long term from the sale of our products. See "ITEM 3. Key Information&#151;D. Risk Factors&#151;Risks Related to our business and our industry&#151;Our
	future revenue growth depends in part on our ability to successfully introduce new products."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Acquisitions
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During the fiscal years ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2016 we completed a number of acquisitions that allowed the Company to expand
	the existing verticals, increase revenue and create new offerings of services currently provided. The Company used the acquisition method of
	accounting to record these business combinations. Acquisitions were settled in cash and/or stock where a portion of the settlement price may have been deferred. For some transactions, purchase
	agreements contain contingent consideration in the form of an earnout obligation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Acquisition of INSYS Group,&nbsp;Inc.
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On July&nbsp;15, 2016, Luxoft USA,&nbsp;Inc. completed the acquisition of INSYS Group,&nbsp;Inc. ("Insys"), an IT consulting
	provider focusing on advanced predictive analytics, business intelligence and data warehousing, digital marketing, and enterprise information management. Luxoft acquired all of the issued and
	outstanding shares of common stock of Insys for an initial payment of $37.9&nbsp;million with the remaining amount payable being subject to certain revenue and EBITDA targets to be achieved by Insys
	for the six-month period ending December&nbsp;31, 2016, and its 2017 and 2018 fiscal years. The total amount of contingent purchase consideration is not to exceed $33.5&nbsp;million. Additionally,
	under the Purchase Agreement, certain managers of Insys are eligible for incentive payments under a management earnout participation plan in an amount of up to $7.0&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Acquisition of Symtavision&nbsp;GmbH
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On February&nbsp;23, 2016, Luxoft Global Operations&nbsp;GmbH, a wholly-owned Swiss subsidiary of the Company ("LGO"), completed
	its acquisition of Symtavision&nbsp;GmbH ("Symtavision"), a boutique provider of automotive software tools and consulting services focused on scheduling analysis, architecture optimization, and
	timing verification. Symtavision's tools, building on its proprietary intellectual property, focus on Under the Hood ("UTH") technology around increasingly important software integration and timing
	analysis in the chassis, powertrain, body, and driver assistance domains as well as in-vehicle networking.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	81
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=86,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=927678,FOLIO='81',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DU75001A.;12',USER='MORAM',CD='26-JUL-2016;19:07' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DU75001_1_82">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Symtavision acquisition enhanced our capabilities in the UTH practice and expanded our list of automotive high potential accounts ("HPAs").
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	accordance with the stock purchase agreement, Luxoft Global Operations&nbsp;GmbH, a wholly-owned Swiss subsidiary of the Company ("LGO") paid a cash purchase price of
	&euro;3.9&nbsp;million, or $4.4&nbsp;million at the then-current exchange rate of &euro;1=$1.14, upon closing of this transaction. Additionally, Luxoft agreed to pay an
	additional &euro;0.5&nbsp;million, or $0.6&nbsp;million, in March 2017 subject to Symtavision achieving certain revenue targets for its 2017 fiscal year. We revalue the contingent
	consideration payable as of the end of each financial reporting period to reflect the then-expected size of the consideration based on the likelihood of Symtavision meeting certain performance
	targets.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Acquisition of Excelian Limited
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On February&nbsp;17, 2015, LGO entered into an agreement (the "Owner Purchase Agreement") to purchase the entire share capital of
	Excelian Limited ("Excelian"), a private company limited by shares incorporated in England and Wales, with the stockholders of Excelian (the "Excelian Sellers"). LGO also entered into separate
	purchase agreements (collectively, the "Option Holder Purchase Agreements" and together with the Owner Purchase Agreement, the "Excelian Purchase Agreements") with several holders of options in
	Excelian (collectively, the "Option Holders") for the exercise of the options and the sale of the shares held by the Option Holders to LGO. These transactions closed on February&nbsp;17 and 18,
	2015. Pursuant to the Excelian Purchase Agreements, LGO agreed, on the terms and subject to the conditions of the Excelian Purchase Agreements, to purchase from the Excelian Sellers and the Option
	Holders all of the issued and outstanding ordinary shares of Excelian for the aggregate consideration payable by the Company of &pound;13.4&nbsp;million or approximately $20.5&nbsp;million
	at the then-current exchange rate of &pound;1=$1.5291.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally,
	certain managers of Excelian were offered after the closing a special class of ordinary shares of Excelian bearing a put right exercisable over three years in annual
	installments, each of one third of the class of shares. The put consideration for these special shares is based on specified EBITDA margin and revenue targets to be achieved by Excelian for its fiscal
	years ending December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2016 and 2017. Based on results for Excelian's 2015 fiscal year, the holders of the put rights have received &pound;0.8&nbsp;million, or
	$1.2&nbsp;million. In the event that Excelian achieves certain EBITDA margin and revenue targets for its 2016 and 2017 fiscal years, as specified in the final documentation for the special shares
	amended during the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, upon exercise of the put right by the holders, Excelian would pay the holders an aggregate amount of up to &pound;2.8&nbsp;million
	or approximately $4.1&nbsp;million at the exchange rate of &pound;1=$1.4393.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Acquisition of Radius&nbsp;Inc.
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On October&nbsp;3, 2014, Luxoft USA, a U.S. subsidiary of the Company, completed its acquisition of Radius&nbsp;Inc. ("Radius"), a
	Washington corporation specializing in delivering IoT enterprise solutions across mobile, cloud, data and application programming interface technologies, pursuant to a Stock Purchase Agreement dated
	October&nbsp;3, 2014 by and among Luxoft USA and the stockholders of Radius (collectively, the "Radius Sellers").
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Radius acquisition added over 100 IT professionals to our headcount and enhanced our capabilities in the IoT practice. It also expanded our list of non-financial HPAs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant
	to the stock purchase agreement ("SPA"), Luxoft USA agreed to purchase from the Radius Sellers all of the issued and outstanding shares of common stock of Radius for an initial
	payment of $19.8&nbsp;million, of which $7.92&nbsp;million was paid at closing and $1.98&nbsp;million in April 2015 after the financial results for the 2014 fiscal year became available. Payment
	of the balance of the initial payment was agreed to be made in two equal instalments following the delivery of financial statements by Radius for its 2015 and 2016 fiscal years. Additionally, the SPA
	provided for a final
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	82
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=87,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=131975,FOLIO='82',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DU75001A.;12',USER='MORAM',CD='26-JUL-2016;19:07' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DU75001_1_83">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	payment
	of up to $7.9&nbsp;million, provided that Radius achieves certain aggregate adjusted EBITDA and revenue CAGR targets for its 2014, 2015 and 2016 fiscal years. The total consideration for the
	acquisition was not to exceed $27.7&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	September 2015, in conjunction with the mutual election under Section&nbsp;338(h) of the U.S. Internal Revenue Code ("Section&nbsp;338(h)"), Luxoft USA and the Radius Sellers
	agreed to treat the Radius purchase as an asset purchase for tax purposes. In accordance with the SPA, Radius Sellers were compensated for the excess taxes they incurred due to the
	Section&nbsp;338(h) election. The increase of $0.69&nbsp;million in the total purchase consideration due to the Section&nbsp;338(h) election was treated as a measurement-period adjustment and
	was allocated to goodwill in our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Effective
	February&nbsp;12, 2016, Luxoft USA and the Radius Sellers agreed to reduce the remaining consideration payable by 15% and fix this portion of consideration. In accordance
	with the amendment to the SPA, the two payments of $4.95&nbsp;million due on April&nbsp;1, 2016 and 2017, respectively, became non-contingent, but were reduced by 15% to $4.21&nbsp;million each.
	The final payment of $7.90&nbsp;million was
	also reduced by 15% to $6.72&nbsp;million and remained contingent, subject to achieving certain revenue targets.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	revalue the contingent consideration payable as of the end of each financial reporting period to reflect the then-expected size of the consideration based on the likelihood of the
	Radius assets meeting certain performance targets. Total gain from revaluation of this consideration for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 amounted to $1.39&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Acquisition of Populus
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Effective June&nbsp;30, 2014, LGO entered into an agreement (the "Purchase Agreement") with Mecel AB ("Mecel"), a Swedish company and
	a subsidiary of Delphi Automotive Systems,&nbsp;LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Delphi"), to acquire intellectual property and related assets comprising Populus software product suite
	("Populus") from Mecel.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant
	to the Purchase Agreement, LGO paid Mecel a cash purchase price for the Populus intellectual property assets consisting of (i)&nbsp;$1.0&nbsp;million at closing and
	(ii)&nbsp;$1.0&nbsp;million in November 2014 upon completion of the agreed-upon Populus knowledge transfer process and the assignment by Mecel to Luxoft of certain customer agreements not assigned
	at closing. Additionally, LGO agreed to pay up to $1.0&nbsp;million during the three years following the closing, representing a portion of the operating income of the acquired Populus business and
	contingent on it meeting certain revenue and gross margin indicators. In September 2015, LGO paid $0.30&nbsp;million in accordance with the Purchase Agreement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Populus
	is a tool used by end users to design, develop and deploy user interfaces for distributed embedded systems. The acquisition allowed us to expand our Human Machine Interface
	("HMI") capabilities to accommodate application development for entry and mid-level car models, as well as for digital clusters. Additionally, this acquisition is expected to present Luxoft with
	licensing opportunities. Finally, having valuable Populus intellectual property assets in its portfolio is expected to enable Luxoft to enhance its competitive offering in automotive HMI,
	infotainment, and digital cluster design.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Certain comprehensive income statement line items
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Sales of services
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales of services consist primarily of the provision of software development, which includes core custom software development and
	support, product engineering and testing and technology consulting services to our clients. Sales of services also includes sales generated from non-core activities, including external project
	consulting, quality management consulting, recruitment services provided to our clients and training services provided to third parties, as well as reimbursements of expenses of our IT
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	83
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=88,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=3633,FOLIO='83',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DU75001A.;12',USER='MORAM',CD='26-JUL-2016;19:07' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DU75001_1_84">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	professionals
	by clients. Historically, non-core sales have accounted for a small portion of total sales. In the past two fiscal years, we derived a substantial majority of the growth in our sales of
	services to existing clients. Below is a discussion of our revenue organized by client location, industry vertical, client concentration and contract type.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Client locations
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We present client location based on the location of the client's key decision-maker. We seek to maintain the current geographical
	balance of sales. Our revenue by client location has generally experienced balanced growth during the periods under review. For more information on sales by client location, see "ITEM 4. Information
	About Luxoft&#151;B. Business Overview&#151;Clients."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Industry Verticals
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;While financial services have historically been our largest industry vertical, we have deep expertise in each of the industry verticals
	we serve. We target six industry verticals within
	which we have maintained a relatively stable revenue mix during the periods under review. For information on sales by industry vertical, see "ITEM 4. Information About Luxoft&#151;B. Business
	Overview&#151;Our verticals."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Client concentration
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We have deep and long-standing relationships with our top clients. As a percentage of total sales, revenue generated by our top five
	clients declined from 71.9% for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, to 64.9% in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016. Revenue generated by our top ten clients for the same periods
	decreased from 80.1% to 73.7% as a percentage of total sales. Over the long-term, we expect client concentration from our top ten clients to continue to decrease as a result of increase in demand from
	other clients, as well as business from new clients. New clients for any period are defined as clients who were not on our client list as of the end of the applicable prior fiscal year. For
	information on sales by client, see "ITEM 4. Information About Luxoft&#151;B. Business Overview&#151;Clients."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Contract types
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We derive revenue from fixed price contracts and time-and-materials contracts. Under time-and-materials contracts, we are compensated
	for actual time incurred by our IT professionals at negotiated hourly, daily or monthly rates. The majority of our fixed price contracts allow monthly or quarterly revenue recognition based on monthly
	and quarterly milestones, with clear customer acceptance criteria that could be assessed at the end of respective periods. We believe the use of proportional performance with monthly or quarterly
	contractual milestones for customer acceptance continues to be an appropriate revenue recognition method for fixed price contracts.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	following table sets forth sales by contract type, by amount and as a percentage of our total sales for the periods indicated:
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=6,SEQ=89,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=61606,FOLIO='84',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DU75001A.;12',USER='MORAM',CD='26-JUL-2016;19:07' -->
<!-- THIS IS THE END OF A COMPOSITION COMPONENT -->
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DW75001_1_85">
</A>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_BASECOLOR,"BLACK" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DEFAULTFONT,"FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLESHADECOLOR,"#CCEEFF" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_STABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:DOUBLE #000000 2.25PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_SCRTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DCRTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:DOUBLE #000000 2.25PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;" -->
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating expenses
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our operating expenses consist of:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Cost of services
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cost of services includes salaries and related benefits for our delivery center employees, compensation for our contractors and other
	project-related costs, including travel, materials and other direct costs. All our IT professionals are salaried employees except for personnel in
	Ukraine, the United States and United Kingdom, the substantial majority of whom are contractors. The majority of our costs of services comprise compensation to our employees and contractors, and we
	expect substantially the same composition of costs of services in the future. Where services are performed by contractors, the entire cost of contractors is included in cost of services. With respect
	to employees, the compensation for the time that our employees log for specific projects in their time sheets is included in our cost of sales, and the remainder of the total compensation for logged
	time is recorded in selling, general and administrative expenses. The travel expenses of our employees and contractors directly related to specific projects are recorded in our cost of services. Cost
	of services also includes social contribution charges payable on the salaries for our employees.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Selling, general and administrative expenses
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Selling expenses include primarily advertising and marketing expenses. General and administrative expenses include compensation and
	other expenses of our senior management, administrative personnel, and R&amp;D personnel, as well as compensation expenses for unassigned time of our IT professionals. General and administrative expenses
	also include office rent and maintenance and professional services, including legal, audit and insurance services, travel and entertainment expenses other than those directly related to projects for
	clients, and other expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Depreciation and amortization
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Depreciation and amortization includes depreciation of property and equipment and amortization of capitalized software costs, acquired
	contract-based client relationships and other intangible assets. We use the straight-line method to determine depreciation and amortization.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Loss/gain from revaluation of contingent liability
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Loss from revaluation of contingent liability includes results from revaluation of contingent liabilities arising as part of business
	combinations. Contingent liabilities are remeasured to fair value at each reporting date until the contingency is resolved.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Other income and expenses
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our other income and expenses consist of:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Interest expense, net:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Interest income and interest expense are accrued by reference to the principal amount outstanding at the
	applicable interest
	rate. We earn interest income on our cash deposits and loans provided to related parties.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other gains/(loss), net:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other gains, net consists of government grants, subleasing office space, operational leasing of equipment and
	disposal of
	old computer equipment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gain/(loss) from foreign currency exchange contracts:
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gain (loss) from foreign currency exchange contracts is represented by gains and
	losses from
	settlement and revaluation of derivatives related to forward foreign currency exchange contracts not designated as cash flow hedges.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	85
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=90,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=509794,FOLIO='85',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DW75001A.;16',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;14:55' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DW75001_1_86">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Starting
	January 2016, due to an increased volume of hedged transactions, extended periods of foreign exchange contracts and a risk of significant fluctuations of fair values of
	derivatives affecting our Statement of Comprehensive income, we started to apply hedge accounting to forward contracts offsetting our forecasted transactions denominated in euro and British pounds.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All
	gain or loss on a derivative instrument designated as a cash flow hedge is recognized in other comprehensive income until reclassified into earnings in the same period when the
	hedged forecasted transaction affects earnings, i.e.&nbsp;when a forecasted sale actually occurs or an expense is incurred. Gains or losses related to hedging of forecasted sales are recognized in
	Sales of services, and those attributable to forecasted expense are recognized in Cost of services.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net foreign exchange income/(loss):
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We enter into foreign exchange transactions as we have contracts denominated in both U.S. dollars,
	euros, rubles,
	and, to a lesser extent, Swiss francs, British pounds and other currencies. Re-measurement of monetary assets, such as receivables, denominated in foreign currencies that are different from functional
	currencies of the respective subsidiaries, result in and are recorded as net foreign exchange income/(loss).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income tax expense
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our income tax includes both current and deferred income taxes. Because we operate in a number of countries, our income is subject to
	taxation in differing jurisdictions with a range of tax rates. Therefore, we need to apply significant judgment to determine our consolidated income tax position. Due to our multi-jurisdictional
	operations, we are exposed to a number of different tax risks including, but not limited to, changes in tax laws or interpretations of these tax laws. During the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31,
	2016, our effective income tax rate increased as a result of an internal restructuring completed the year before to better align our legal and operating structures, and due to acquisitions of new
	businesses in Germany, the United States and the United Kingdom completed in the fiscal years ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	86
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DW75001_1_87">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Results of operations
</B>
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 compared to fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Sales of services
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, our revenues demonstrated 25.0% growth year over year, increasing by
	$130.2&nbsp;million to $650.8&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 from $520.5&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. All our verticals, except for
	travel and aviation, experienced growth during the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, while the main increase is attributable to increased volume of sales in our largest verticals, financial
	services and automotive and transport, which contributed 19.2% and 4.1% of overall growth, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;From
	a geographical standpoint, our revenue increased substantially due to our UK clients, providing 12.2% of overall revenue growth, as well as clients from Germany and Switzerland,
	contributing 4.2% and 2.4% of total revenue growth, respectively. In comparison to the prior fiscal year, in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, our revenue generated from the UK clients
	increased by 39.8% from 30.7% to 34.4% of total revenue; Germany increased by 33.4% from 12.4% to 13.3% of the total and Switzerland increased by 117.5% from 2.1% to 3.6% of the total. The increase in
	sales of services to our UK clients resulted both from increased volume of sales to our top clients in the
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	87
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=92,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=477456,FOLIO='87',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DW75001A.;16',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;14:55' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DW75001_1_88">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	financial
	services vertical as well as revenue from the Excelian business, which was acquired in February 2015. The increase in revenue from our clients in Germany and Switzerland is attributable
	mainly to increased volume of sales to clients in the financial and automotive and transport verticals.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	continuously develop relations with our clients and as a result, sales to our existing clients accounted for 81.3% of the increase in sales of services for the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2016, while sales to new clients accounted for 19.4% of the increase. Sales of services to new clients represented 3.9% of total sales in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016,
	as compared to 4.5% of total sales in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. Our non-core sales accounted for 0.2% and 0.5% of total sales in the years ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015,
	respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To
	support our growing sales, we increased the number of our IT professionals to 9,239 as of March&nbsp;31, 2016, from 7,850 IT professionals as of March&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating expenses
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Cost of services
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cost of services increased by $85.4&nbsp;million, or 29.0%, to $379.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016
	from $294.0&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. Gross margin decreased from 43.5% to 41.7% in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, when compared to the prior fiscal
	year. The increase in cost of services and related decrease in gross margin was attributable primarily to the growth of personnel expenses directly attributable to client projects as a result of
	increased headcount in the locations with higher salaries.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	a percentage of sales, cost of services increased to 58.3% for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, from 56.5% in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Selling, general and administrative expenses
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, our selling, general and administrative expenses increased by $42.8&nbsp;million,
	or 33.2%, to $171.7&nbsp;million. As a percentage of sales, selling, general and administrative expenses increased to 26.4% for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, from 24.8% in the fiscal
	year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. This increase was attributable to a number of factors, including the stock option plan implemented in December 2014 and expansion of our business functions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Payroll
	and bonuses expenses with payroll taxes (excluding share-based compensation) increased by $21.5&nbsp;million, or 35.5%, from $60.5&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2015 to $82.0&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, primarily due to expansion of our R&amp;D activities and sales team. Share-based compensation increased by
	$12.0&nbsp;million from $5.8&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 to $17.7&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, mainly due to the timing of the
	stock-based compensation program, which was launched in late 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	continued to invest in our infrastructure. To accommodate the increased headcount, we rented new facilities which resulted in a $5.6&nbsp;million, or 19.3%, increase in general and
	administrative expenses due to an increase in office rent and maintenance expenses to $34.6&nbsp;million for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 from $29.0&nbsp;million for the fiscal year
	ended March&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Depreciation and amortization
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Depreciation and amortization increased by $7.0&nbsp;million, or 41.5%, to $23.8&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2016 from $16.8&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase was attributable primarily to depreciation of computers and office equipment due to
	increased headcount, as well as amortization of customer relationships related to acquisitions of Radius and Excelian. As a percentage of sales, depreciation and amortization increased from 3.2% in
	the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 to 3.7% in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	88
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income from revaluation of contingent liability
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The financial results from revaluation of contingent liability changed by $3.7&nbsp;million from a loss of $1.2&nbsp;million in the
	fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 to a gain of $2.5&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 mainly due to the agreement with the Sellers of Radius&nbsp;Inc. to reduce the
	remaining consideration payable by 15% discussed above under "
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Acquisition of Radius&nbsp;Inc.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	"; and due to a shift in timing of previously expected
	revenues, subject to contingent royalty payments beyond the royalty period ending December&nbsp;31, 2017.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating income
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Due to the increases in cost of services and general and administrative expenses discussed above, our operating income decreased by
	$1.2&nbsp;million, or 1.5%, to $78.4&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 from $79.6&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. As a percentage of sales,
	operating income decreased to 12.0% in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, from 15.3% for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Other income and expenses
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Other gain/(loss), net
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other gains increased by $2.5&nbsp;million from $1.4&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 to
	$3.9&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016. The increase is attributable to $2.9&nbsp;million from three government grants received in Romania, Poland and Bulgaria during the
	fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, partially offset by a $0.4&nbsp;million decrease in income from operating leases of IT equipment in one of our subsidiaries.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Gain from foreign currency exchange contracts
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gain from foreign currency exchange contracts decreased by $1.0&nbsp;million from $1.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2015 to $0.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, mainly due to decreased fluctuation in the U.S. dollar/euro exchange rates during the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2016, when compared to the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, resulting in lower gains realized on our euro/U.S. dollar forward contracts.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net foreign exchange loss
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net foreign exchange loss decreased by $8.5&nbsp;million from $8.9&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 to
	$0.4&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	loss in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 was driven primarily by the depreciation of the euro against the U.S. dollar, which resulted in losses from our euro-denominated
	receivables. During the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, the euro depreciated against the U.S. dollar by 3% while during the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, the euro depreciated
	against the U.S. dollar by 11%. Also, in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, the Russian ruble depreciated significantly against the U.S. dollar, which affected adversely our
	Ruble-denominated receivables. During the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, the Russian ruble depreciated against the U.S. dollar by 14% while during the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31,
	2015, the Russian ruble depreciated against the U.S. dollar by 39%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income from continuing operations before income taxes
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income from continuing operations before income taxes increased by $9.4&nbsp;million, or 12.9%, to $82.4&nbsp;million in the fiscal
	year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, from $73.0&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, and demonstrated a decrease as a percentage of sales from 14.0% to 12.7% in the years ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2016, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	89
</FONT>
</P>
