</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income tax expense
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income tax expense increased by $2.3&nbsp;million, or 23.2%, to $12.1&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016
	from $9.8&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. Our
	effective income tax rate increased to 14.7% of income from continuing operations before income taxes in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, from 13.5% in the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2015. The rate increase represents a combined effect of our acquisitions completed during the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, which increased the portion of our taxable
	profits attributable to jurisdictions with higher tax rates, and an overall increase in taxable profits in Switzerland, the United Kingdom and the United States.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 compared to fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Sales of services
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales of services increased by $122.2&nbsp;million, or 30.7%, to $520.5&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015
	from $398.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. The growth in sales of services resulted primarily from increased sales to existing clients. The growth in sales of services
	was supported by the expansion of services performed for clients across our largest verticals, including financial services, automotive and transport and technology. Sales to existing clients
	accounted for 85.9% of the increase in sales of services for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, while sales to new clients accounted for 13.7% of the increase. Sales of services to new
	clients represented 4.5% of total sales in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, as compared to 1.7% of total sales in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. Non-core sales accounted for
	0.5% of total sales in the years ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014. To support our growing sales, we increased the number of our IT professionals to 7,850 as of March&nbsp;31, 2015, from 6,366 IT
	professionals as of March&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating expenses
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Cost of services
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cost of services increased by $64.5&nbsp;million, or 28.1%, to $294.0&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015
	from $229.5&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. The increase was attributable primarily to the growth of personnel expenses directly attributable to client projects.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cost
	of services also increased as a result of an increased number of IT professionals as well as wage inflation for project delivery personnel. As a percentage of sales, Cost of
	services decreased to 56.5% for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, from 57.6% in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Selling, general and administrative expenses
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Selling, general and administrative expenses increased by $33.1&nbsp;million, or 34.5%, to $129.0&nbsp;million in the fiscal year
	ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 from $95.9&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. As a percentage of sales, selling, general and administrative expenses increased to 24.8% for the
	fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, from 24.1% in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. This increase was attributable to a number of factors, including acquisition related expenses and a
	new stock option plan implemented in December 2014. All major types of general and administrative expenses experienced growth in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. Payroll and bonuses
	expenses with payroll taxes (excluding share-based compensation) increased by $11.3&nbsp;million from $48.8&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014 to $60.1&nbsp;million in
	the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. Share-based compensation increased by $4.4&nbsp;million from $1.4&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014 to $5.8&nbsp;million in
	the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. General and administrative expenses also increased because of an increase in office rent and maintenance expenses by $4.1&nbsp;million to
	$29.0&nbsp;million for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 from $24.9&nbsp;million for the fiscal year ended
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	90
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=95,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=135364,FOLIO='90',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DY75001A.;20',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;14:58' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DY75001_1_91">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	March&nbsp;31,
	2014, due to the rental of new facilities to accommodate increasing headcount. Expenses for professional services, including the outsourcing of administrative functions, auditing,
	legal and consulting services as well as non-billable independent contractors, increased by $8.8&nbsp;million from $14.1&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014 to
	$22.9&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31,
	2015. During fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 we incurred costs related to acquisitions of new businesses. No similar expenses were incurred in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Depreciation and amortization
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Depreciation and amortization increased by $3.9&nbsp;million, or 30.1%, to $16.8&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2015 from $12.9&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. The increase was attributable primarily to amortization of customer relationships and to depreciation of
	a greater number of fixed assets resulting from purchases of new IT equipment, leasehold improvements and software licenses. As a percentage of sales, Depreciation and amortization remained at the
	same level of 3.2% for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 compared to the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating income
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating income increased by $20.6&nbsp;million, or 34.9%, to $79.6&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015
	from $59.0&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. As a percentage of sales, operating income increased to 15.3% for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, from 14.8% in
	the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating
	income increased in absolute terms and as a percentage of sales from our previous fiscal year mainly due to combined effect of revenue growth and efficient management of our
	costs of services partially offset by an increase in general and administrative expenses due to wage inflation, share-based compensation and one-off costs related to the acquisitions of new
	businesses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Other income and expenses
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Interest expense, net
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Interest expense decreased by $1.0&nbsp;million, or 66.3%, to $0.5&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 from
	$1.5&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. The decrease was due to the repayment of all our previously obtained loans, with only one loan from an acquired subsidiary remaining
	outstanding as of March&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Other gain/(loss), net
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other gains increased by $0.8&nbsp;million from $0.6&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014 to
	$1.4&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. This increase is mainly attributable to income from operating leases of IT equipment in one of our subsidiaries.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Gain/(loss) from foreign currency exchange contracts
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gain/(loss) from foreign currency exchange contracts changed by $2.4&nbsp;million from a loss of $1.1&nbsp;million in the fiscal
	year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014 to a gain of $1.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 mainly due to gains realized on several euro/U.S. dollar forward contracts.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net foreign exchange loss
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net foreign exchange loss increased by $7.9&nbsp;million from $1.0&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014 to
	$8.9&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. The loss in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 was driven primarily by the depreciation of the euro against the U.S.
	dollar, which resulted in losses from our euro-denominated receivables. Also, in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, the Russian ruble depreciated significantly against the U.S. dollar, which
	affected adversely our ruble denominated receivables.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	91
</FONT>
</P>

	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income from continuing operations before income taxes
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income from continuing operations before income taxes increased by $17.1&nbsp;million, or 30.6%, to $73.0&nbsp;million in the
	fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 from $55.9&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014 and remained flat as a percentage of sales at 14.0% in both years under review.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income tax expense
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income tax expense increased by $5.1&nbsp;million, or 108.4%, to $9.8&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015
	from $4.7&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. The increase was attributable primarily to an increase in taxable profits in Switzerland, Russia, Romania and the United
	States. Our effective income tax rate increased to 13.5% of income from continuing operations before income taxes in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, from 8.4% in the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Quarterly results of operations and seasonality
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our business is moderately seasonal and our results of operations vary from quarter to quarter based in part upon the budget and work
	cycles of our clients. Our operating results are typically lower in the first fiscal quarter of each year due to increases in wages and other costs that typically occur in the beginning of each fiscal
	year. The following table presents our unaudited condensed consolidated quarterly results of operations for the eight quarters in the period from April&nbsp;1, 2014 to March&nbsp;31, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=97,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=944157,FOLIO='92',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DY75001A.;20',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;14:58' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DY75001_1_93">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_DY_5B">
</A>
	B.&nbsp;&nbsp;Liquidity and Capital Resources
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At March, 2016, our principal sources of liquidity were cash and cash equivalents totaling $108.5&nbsp;million and $65.7&nbsp;million of available borrowings
	under our revolving lines of credit. As of that date, $94.9&nbsp;million was held in U.S. dollar denominated accounts primarily in Switzerland and BVI.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under
	the legislation of the countries we operate in, there are no restrictions on our ability to distribute dividends from our subsidiaries to our parent company other than a
	requirement that dividends be limited to the cumulative net profits of our operating subsidiaries, calculated in accordance with local accounting principles. The cumulative net profit of our
	subsidiaries calculated in accordance with local accounting principles differs from the cumulative net profit calculated in accordance with U.S.&nbsp;GAAP primarily due to the treatment of accrued
	expenses and differences arising from the capitalization and depreciation of property and equipment. In addition, these dividends cannot result in negative net assets at our subsidiaries or render
	them insolvent.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	have not provided for dividend withholding taxes on the unremitted earnings of our subsidiaries because they are considered permanently reinvested.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	cash requirements have principally been driven by working capital requirements and capital expenditures. Our working capital requirements are, in turn, generally driven by the growth
	in our business and the impact on our cash flows arising out of the difference in timing between when our payment obligations arise and when we receive payment from clients. We fund working capital
	primarily from cash and cash equivalents on hand, cash flows provided by our operating activities and our short term credit facilities in those cases when it is deemed necessary or most efficient way.
	Our average time for collecting receivables, which include trade receivables, unbilled revenue and deferred revenue balances, decreased to 76&nbsp;days for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31,
	2016, from 81&nbsp;days for the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, mainly due to increased efficiency of our collecting cycle.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	of march 31, 2016, we did not have any material commitments for capital expenditures.We believe that, based on our current business plan, our cash and cash equivalents on hand, cash
	from operations and borrowings available to us will be adequate to meet our working capital, capital expenditure requirements and liquidity needs for the foreseeable future. We may require additional
	capital to meet our longer term liquidity and future growth requirements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Credit facilities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On January&nbsp;15, 2013, the Company entered into an uncommitted receivables purchase agreement of up to $10.0&nbsp;million with
	BNP Paribas Dublin Branch. Under the agreement the Company can assign certain receivables in exchange for cash based on LIBOR for the relevant purchase term (30/60&nbsp;days) plus 3.0% per annum. On
	October&nbsp;30, 2015, BNP Paribas increased the amount of credit limit available to the Company up to $20.0&nbsp;million. There was no outstanding amount as of March&nbsp;31, 2016 under this
	agreement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	November&nbsp;20, 2013, Luxoft UK&nbsp;Ltd., Luxoft Eastern Europe&nbsp;Ltd. and Luxoft GMBH entered into an uncommitted Pre- and Post-Shipment Advances Facility Agreement with
	Citibank Europe&nbsp;PLC for up to $5.0&nbsp;million. On November&nbsp;13, 2014 LGO acceded to the mentioned Facility Agreement as one of the borrowers thereunder. On January&nbsp;29, 2016
	Citibank increased the total credit amount available for the Company to $12.0&nbsp;million. This is a continuing agreement and remains in full effect subject to its terms until 30&nbsp;days after
	the bank`s receipt of written notice of termination from the borrower's agent. Under this agreement the borrower can use pre- or post-shipment advance. The interest rate for pre-shipment is LIBOR plus
	2.0% p.a. and the interest rate for post-shipment is LIBOR plus 1.25% per annum. There was no outstanding amount as of March&nbsp;31, 2016 under this agreement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	93
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=98,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=833600,FOLIO='93',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DY75001A.;20',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;14:58' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DY75001_1_94">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	February&nbsp;20, 2014, Luxoft USA entered into a credit facility agreement with Citibank, N.A. for up to $5.5&nbsp;million. The loan bears an interest rate
	LIBOR&nbsp;+&nbsp;1.25% per annum. There was no outstanding amount as of March&nbsp;31, 2016 under this agreement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	July&nbsp;16 2010, Luxoft USA and on April&nbsp;9, 2015, LGO respectively entered into a credit agreement with Amsterdam Trade Bank&nbsp;N.V. for an aggregate available credit
	amount of up to $18.0&nbsp;million. For both facilities, the interest rate is the cumulative of the applicable LIBOR and a margin which varies in relation to term of the loan in the range of
	4.5-5.5%. There was no outstanding amount as of March&nbsp;31, 2016 under these agreements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Excelian&nbsp;Ltd,
	uses an invoice discounting facility of up to &pound;3.0&nbsp;million provided by Royal Bank of Scotland. Under this arrangement Excelian&nbsp;Ltd can
	assign certain receivables in exchange for cash less a discount based of 1.90% per annum. The outstanding amount was $0.8&nbsp;million as of March&nbsp;31, 2015 and there was no amount outstanding
	as of March&nbsp;31, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Overdraft facilities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On October&nbsp;25, 2012, Luxoft Professional,&nbsp;LLC entered into an overdraft facility agreement with ZAO CITIBANK for
	$3.0&nbsp;million. As of March&nbsp;31, 2016, this facility has not been drawn down. The overdraft facility bears interest at a rate of LIBOR (1M) plus 2.25% per annum overnight interest rate paid
	monthly. The overdraft facility is guaranteed by Luxoft Holding,&nbsp;Inc.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	November&nbsp;12, 2013, Luxoft Professional Romania SRL entered into an overdraft facility agreement with ZAO CITIBANK for $0.9&nbsp;million. As of March&nbsp;31, 2016, this
	facility has not been drawn down. The overdraft facility bears interest at a rate of LIBOR (1M) plus 2.00% per annum overnight interest rate paid monthly. The overdraft facility is guaranteed by
	Luxoft Holding,&nbsp;Inc. and Luxoft Professional,&nbsp;LLC.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	December&nbsp;16, 2009, Luxoft International entered into an overdraft facility agreement with Amsterdam Trade Bank,&nbsp;N.V. ("Amsterdam Trade Bank") for up to
	$1.6&nbsp;million, which was later amended to increase the overdraft facility to up to $2.0&nbsp;million. On July&nbsp;20, 2012, Luxoft International renewed the overdraft facility agreement
	with Amsterdam Trade Bank for $2.0&nbsp;million. As of March&nbsp;31, 2015, this facility had not been drawn down. The overdraft facility bears interest at a rate of 6.0% per annum, paid monthly.
	Initially the overdraft facility was guaranteed by IBS Group. On February&nbsp;5, 2014 the guarantor was replaced by Luxoft Holding,&nbsp;Inc. The facility was drawn down on July&nbsp;20, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net cash provided by operating activities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net cash provided by operating activities increased by $29.1&nbsp;million, or 38.2%, to $105.4&nbsp;million in the fiscal year
	ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, from $76.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase is explained primarily by higher net income from continuing operations adjusted for
	non-cash stock based compensation expense, demonstrating an overall increase of $19.1&nbsp;million from $68.9&nbsp;million to $88.0&nbsp;million, where stock based compensation expense
	contributed $12.0&nbsp;million of
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	94
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=6,SEQ=99,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=117310,FOLIO='94',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]DY75001A.;20',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;14:58' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_DY75001_1_95">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	such
	increase. Another $8.1&nbsp;million increase in cash flows from operating activities was attributable to a decrease of amounts due from and to clients from $22.7&nbsp;million in the fiscal
	year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 to $14.6&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, as a result of increased efficiency of our collecting cycle discussed above.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net
	cash provided by operating activities increased by $25.6&nbsp;million, or 50.6%, to $76.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, from $50.7&nbsp;million
	in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. The increase in cash flows from operating activities was attributable primarily to higher net income from continuing operations, adjusted for stock
	based compensation which increased by $16.3&nbsp;million, from $52.6&nbsp;million to $68.9&nbsp;million. Also, operating cash flows benefited, in part, from our strong focus on improving working
	capital efficiencies during the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, including our focus on reducing days outstanding for our full accounts receivable including trade receivables and unbilled
	revenues, excluding deferred revenues and adjusted for the effects of foreign exchange.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net cash used in investing activities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net cash used in investing activities decreased by $9.6&nbsp;million, or 22.6%, to $32.7&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2016, from $42.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. The change was mainly due to decreased investments in acquisitions of new businesses which amounted to
	$24.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, and $3.5&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016. This decrease was partially offset by increased investments
	in our existing businesses, in particular purchases of new electronic and office equipment and other purchases of property and equipment, which increased from $14.2&nbsp;million to
	$24.2&nbsp;million when comparing the years ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2016, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net
	cash used in investing activities increased by $23.1&nbsp;million to $42.3&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 from $19.1&nbsp;million in the fiscal
	year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014. Investing activities in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 consisted mainly of acquisitions of new business which increased in fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2015 by $24.3&nbsp;million from nil in fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net cash used in financing activities
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cash used in financing activities decreased by $13.1&nbsp;million to $8.9&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31,
	2016, from $22.0&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015. The decrease was primarily attributable to repayment of short-term borrowings, amounting to $0.9&nbsp;million and
	$18.6&nbsp;million in the years ended March&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, respectively, partially offset by an increase in the amount of deferred purchase consideration paid for acquired businesses from
	$2.7&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015, to $ 6.1&nbsp;million in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, and repurchase of ordinary shares in amount of
	$1.8&nbsp;million as a result of personal income taxes withheld from SOP III participants upon exercise of vested RSUs, SARs and PSAs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net
	cash used in financing activities increased by $23.6&nbsp;million to $22.0&nbsp;million used in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2015 from $1.6&nbsp;million cash provided
	by financing activities in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	primary driver for the increase in cash used in financing activities was $18.6&nbsp;million of short-term borrowings repayment net of proceeds in the fiscal year ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2015 which represents an increase of $22.3&nbsp;million when compared to short-term borrowings proceeds net of repayment generated in in the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2014.
	Also, net cash used in financing activities includes repayment of contingent payables related to business acquisitions of $2.7&nbsp;million and $2.4&nbsp;million in the years ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. Net effect from other changes is not deemed material.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	95
</FONT>

	Table of Contents

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Critical accounting policies
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We prepare our consolidated financial statements in accordance with U.S.&nbsp;GAAP, which requires us to make judgments, estimates
	and assumptions that affect: (i)&nbsp;the reported amounts of assets and liabilities; (ii)&nbsp;disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the end of each reporting period; and
	(iii)&nbsp;the reported amounts of sales and expenses during each reporting period. The most significant estimates relate to the recognition of revenue, allowance for doubtful accounts, income
	taxes, goodwill and other long-lived assets, assumptions used in valuing share-based compensation awards and contingencies. We evaluate these estimates and assumptions based on historical experience,
	knowledge and assessment of current business and other conditions, and expectations regarding the future based on available information and reasonable assumptions, which together form&nbsp;a basis
	for making judgments about matters not readily apparent from other sources. Since the use of estimates is an integral component of the financial reporting process, actual results could differ from
	those estimates. Some of our accounting policies require higher degrees of judgment than others in their application. When reviewing our consolidated financial statements, you should consider
	(i)&nbsp;our selection of critical accounting policies, (ii)&nbsp;the judgment and other uncertainties
	affecting the application of such policies and (iii)&nbsp;the sensitivity of reported results to changes in conditions and assumptions. We consider the policies discussed below to be critical to an
	understanding of our consolidated financial statements as their application places significant demands on the judgment of our management.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;An
	accounting policy is considered to be critical if it requires an accounting estimate to be made based on assumptions about matters that are highly uncertain at the time the estimate
	is made, and if different estimates that reasonably could have been used, or changes in the accounting estimates that are reasonably likely to occur periodically, could materially impact the
	consolidated financial statements. We believe that the following critical accounting policies are the most sensitive and require more significant estimates and assumptions used in the preparation of
	our consolidated financial statements. You should read the following descriptions of critical accounting policies, judgments and estimates in conjunction with our consolidated financial statements and
	other disclosures included in this annual report.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	an "emerging growth company" under the JOBS Act, we take advantage of exemptions from various reporting requirements applicable to public companies that are not emerging growth
	companies. See "ITEM 3. Key Information&#151;D. Risk Factors&#151;We are an 'emerging growth company' with reduced reporting requirements, which may make our Class&nbsp;A ordinary
	shares less attractive to investors." However, we have irrevocably elected to opt out of the extended transition period for complying with new or revised accounting standards provided by
	Section&nbsp;107(b) of the JOBS Act. As a result, we will comply with new or revised accounting standards on the relevant dates on which adoption of such standards is required for public companies
	that do not qualify as "emerging growth companies."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Revenue recognition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company derives its revenues from software development services, including in such areas of competence as (a)&nbsp;custom
	software development and support, (b)&nbsp;product engineering and testing and (c)&nbsp;technology consulting.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenues
	under time and materials and fixed price contracts are recognized in the period in which these services are performed and contract stages are accepted by clients by using a
	proportional performance method. We consider amounts to be earned once evidence of an arrangement has been obtained, services are delivered, fees are fixed or determinable, and collectability is
	reasonably assured. In such contracts, our services, measured by time incurred, typically are provided in less than a year and represent the contractual stages or output measures which define the
	pattern of contractual earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	96
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=101,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=483854,FOLIO='96',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]EA75001A.;14',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;15:15' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_EA75001_1_97">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	complexity of the estimation process and factors relating to the assumptions, risks and uncertainties inherent with the application of the proportional performance method of
	accounting affects the amounts of sales reported in our consolidated financial statements. A number of internal and external factors can affect our estimates, including labor hours and changes in
	specification and testing requirements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Time-and-material contracts.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We recognize sales from time-and-material contracts as services are performed, based on actual hours and
	applicable
	billing rates, using the proportional performance method, with the corresponding cost of providing those services reflected as cost of sales. The majority of such sales are billed on a monthly basis
	whereby actual time is charged directly to the client at negotiated hourly billing rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fixed price contracts.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We recognize sales from fixed price contracts based on the proportional performance method, during the period in
	which amounts
	become billable in accordance with the terms of the contracts. Services under fixed price contracts are delivered in stages. Revenues recognized for completed stages are generally representative of
	the percentage of completion of the entire contract, as they are based on actual hours incurred compared with the total hours estimated to complete the entire contract. Costs related to completed
	stages are expensed as incurred, while those related to uncompleted stages are recorded in work-in-progress on the balance sheet. In instances where final acceptance is specified by the client, sales
	are deferred until all acceptance criteria have been met. In the absence of a sufficient basis to measure progress towards completion, sales are recognized upon receipt of final acceptance from the
	client. We have not yet had any significant contracts for which estimates of completion could not be developed or final project completion and client acceptance was so uncertain as to require deferral
	of revenue until the completion of the project.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Multiple elements arrangements.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During the fiscal year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, we have entered into multiple elements arrangements
	with the
	customers that purchase software and further maintenance and support. We evaluate our contracts for multiple deliverables, and, when appropriate, separate the contracts into separate units of
	accounting for revenue recognition. Support services, if they are required by clients, are generally contracted for and commence upon completion of the software development services. We allocate
	revenue to these deliverables in a multiple element arrangement based upon their relative selling prices. The relative selling price is based on the price charged for the deliverable when it is sold
	separately. For multiple element arrangements under time-and-material contracts, revenue is recognized as services are performed for each deliverable based on hours incurred
	and applicable hourly rates. For arrangements under fixed price contracts, software development revenue is recognized upon delivery of development services under the proportional performance method,
	as described above and for support services&#151;on a straight-line basis over the support period, which is generally from 6&nbsp;months to a year.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	report gross reimbursable travel and "out-of-pocket" expenses incurred as both sales and cost of sales in the consolidated statements of comprehensive income.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Accounts receivable
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Accounts receivable are shown at their net realizable value, which approximates their fair value. Since we generally do not require
	collateral or other security from our clients, we establish an allowance for doubtful accounts based upon estimates, historical experience and other factors surrounding the credit risk of specific
	clients. Allowances for doubtful accounts are made for specific accounts in which collectability is doubtful. If the financial condition of our clients were to deteriorate, resulting in an impairment
	of their ability to make payments, additional allowances may be required. Recoveries of losses from accounts receivable written off in prior years are presented within income from operations on our
	consolidated statements of comprehensive income.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	97
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=102,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=139460,FOLIO='97',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]EA75001A.;14',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;15:15' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_EA75001_1_98">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	client base primarily consists of large multinational companies. The timing of invoicing and collection of our accounts receivable under our contracts is impacted by the life cycle
	of each project and related payment milestones.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	management periodically monitors outstanding receivables and collection status and assesses the adequacy of allowances for accounts where collection may be in doubt as frequency and
	amount of client defaults change due to our clients' financial condition or general economic conditions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Goodwill
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Goodwill represents an excess of the cost of business acquired over the fair value of the amounts assigned to tangible and intangible
	assets acquired less liabilities assumed. The determination of the fair value of intangible assets acquired involves certain judgments and estimates. These judgments can include, but are not limited
	to, the cash flows that an asset is expected to generate in the future and the appropriate weighted average cost of capital.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	perform a test for impairment annually, or when indications of potential impairment exist, utilizing a fair value approach at the reporting unit level. We determine fair value using
	the income approach, which estimates the fair value of our operating units based on the future discounted cash flows.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	basis for the cash flow assumptions includes forecasted revenue, operational costs and other relevant factors, including estimated capital expenditures. Assumptions under this method
	have been adjusted to reflect increased risk due to current economic volatility. In testing for a potential impairment of goodwill, we estimate the fair value of our operating units to which goodwill
	relates and determine the carrying value (book value) of the assets and liabilities related to those operating units. If an impairment of goodwill has occurred, we recognize a loss for the difference
	between the carrying amount and the implied fair value of goodwill.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Long-lived assets
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We amortize intangible assets, principally software and acquired contract-based client relationships, on a straight-line basis over
	their estimated useful lives. We review long-lived assets, including intangible assets that are subject to amortization, for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the
	carrying amount of an asset may not be recoverable. We base our evaluation on such impairment indicators as the nature of the assets, the future economic benefit of the assets, any historical or
	future profitability measurements, as well as other external market conditions or factors that may be present. The carrying value is not recoverable if it exceeds the undiscounted future cash flows
	resulting from the use of the asset and its eventual disposition. If impairment has occurred, we measure any impairment of intangible assets based on a projected discounted cash flow method using a
	discount rate determined by our management to be commensurate with the risk inherent in our business. If such assets were determined to be impaired, we recognize a loss for the difference between the
	carrying amount and the fair value of the asset.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Government Grants
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We participates in government grants programs in several countries. Due to the absence of authoritative regulations for government
	grants in U.S.&nbsp;GAAP, we base our accounting on IFRS guidance as a non-authoritative source. We recognize a grant as non-operating income based on the evidence that the company has fulfilled the
	requirements of the program and the grant was received.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	98
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=103,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=1041072,FOLIO='98',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]EA75001A.;14',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;15:15' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_EA75001_1_99">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income taxes
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Determining the consolidated provision for income tax expense, deferred income tax assets and liabilities and related valuation
	allowance, if any, involves judgment. We are required to calculate and provide for income taxes in each of the jurisdictions where we operate. Changes in the geographic mix or estimated level of
	annual pre-tax income can also affect the overall effective income tax rate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Because
	we operate in a number of countries, our income is subject to taxation in differing jurisdictions with a range of tax rates. Therefore, we need to apply significant judgment in
	order to determine our consolidated income tax position. As a result of our multi-jurisdictional operations, we are exposed to a number of different tax risks including, but not limited to, changes in
	tax laws or interpretations of these tax laws. The tax authorities in the jurisdictions where we operate may audit our tax returns and may disagree with the position taken in those returns. An adverse
	outcome resulting from any settlement or future examination of our tax returns may result in additional tax liabilities and may adversely affect our effective tax rate, which could have a material
	adverse effect on our financial position, results of operations and liquidity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Deferred
	tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the estimated future tax consequences of temporary differences between the consolidated financial statement carrying amounts and
	their respective tax bases at each reporting date. Deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured using enacted tax rates expected to apply to taxable income in the year in which the temporary
	differences are expected to be reversed. Changes to enacted tax rates would result in either increases or decreases
	in the provision for income taxes in the period of changes. We evaluate the realization of deferred tax assets and recognize a valuation allowance when it is more likely than not that all or a portion
	of deferred tax assets will not be realized.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	realization of deferred tax assets is primarily dependent on future taxable income. Any reduction in estimated forecasted results may require that we record valuation allowances
	against deferred tax assets. Once a valuation allowance has been established, it will be maintained until there is sufficient positive evidence to conclude that it is more likely than not that the
	deferred tax assets will be realized.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If
	the allowance is reversed in a future period, the income tax provision will be correspondingly reduced. Accordingly, the increase and decrease of valuation allowances could have a
	significant negative or positive impact on future earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	provision for income taxes also includes the impact of provisions established for uncertain income tax positions, as well as the related interest and penalties. Tax exposures can
	involve complex issues and may require an extended period to resolve. Although we believe we have adequately reserved for our uncertain tax positions, no assurance can be given that the final tax
	outcome of these matters will not be different. We adjust these reserves in light of changing facts and circumstances, such as the closing of a tax audit or the refinement of an estimate. To the
	extent that the final tax outcome of these matters differs from the amounts recorded, such differences will impact the provision for income taxes in the period in which such determination is made.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Accounting for share-based employee compensation plans
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Share-based employee compensation is determined based on the grant date fair value of the awards ultimately expected to vest. We
	recognize these compensation costs on a straight-line basis over the requisite service period of the entire award, provided it is no less than the amount that would have been recognized for the vested
	portion of the award.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	the past, we have declared and paid dividends, including with respect to the years ended March&nbsp;31, 2013 and 2012. However, we do not plan to pay regular dividends on any of our
	shares in the foreseeable future. While we currently intend to retain all available funds and any future earnings
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	99
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=104,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=820190,FOLIO='99',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]EA75001A.;14',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;15:15' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_EA75001_1_100">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	to
	fund the development and growth of our business, we may, by a resolution of the board of directors, authorize a special one-time dividend or other form of distribution to our shareholders at such
	time and such amount as board of directors determine to be appropriate and in the best interest of the Company. As a result, if we do not pay dividends, capital appreciation, if any, of our
	Class&nbsp;A ordinary shares will be investors' sole source of gain for the foreseeable future. Any future determination regarding the reservation of part of the profits and distributions to
	shareholders will depend on a range of factors, including the availability of distributable profits, our liquidity and financial position, restrictions imposed by our financing arrangements, tax
	considerations, planned acquisitions, strategic plans of the Company and other relevant factors.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	expected life of an option usually represents the weighted-average period during which our option awards are expected to be outstanding. We have no experience or history to be able
	to determine the expected life over which our option awards will be held before exercise. However, we believe it is reasonable to assume exercise or issuance upon vesting, since the exercise price is
	nil.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If
	any of the assumptions used in the valuation model changes significantly, share-based compensation for future awards may differ materially compared to awards previously granted.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	estimate forfeitures at the time of a grant and revise our estimates, if necessary, in subsequent periods if actual forfeitures or vesting differ from those estimates. The assumptions
	used in the valuation model are based on subjective future expectations combined with management judgment. We have no past history of option forfeitures, but the retention rate amongst our key
	employees and management has historically been high. Therefore, our forfeiture rate is expected to be insignificant. As a result, we have applied an estimated forfeiture rate of nil. If the actual
	forfeiture rate is materially different from the estimate, share-based compensation expense could be materially lower than what has been recorded.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Recent accounting pronouncements
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In May 2014, the FASB issued Accounting Standards Update 2014-09, "
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Revenue from Contracts with
	Customers
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	" ("ASU 2014-09"). ASU 2014-09 will replace all current U.S.&nbsp;GAAP guidance on this topic and eliminate all industry-specific guidance. The new guidance
	(i)&nbsp;removes inconsistencies, and weaknesses in revenue requirements, (ii)&nbsp;provides a more robust framework for addressing revenue issues, (iii)&nbsp;improves comparability of revenue
	recognition practices across entities, industries, jurisdictions, and capital markets, (iv)&nbsp;provides more useful information to users of financial statements through improved disclosure
	requirements, and (v)&nbsp;simplifies the
	preparation of financial statements by reducing the number of requirements to which an entity must refer. The core principle is that an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of
	promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration for which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. The guidance is effective for
	annual reporting periods beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2016 including interim periods within that reporting period. We plan to apply the new standard beginning January&nbsp;1, 2017 either
	retrospectively to each period presented or as a cumulative-effect adjustment as of the date of adoption. The adoption of ASU 2014-09 is not expected to have a material impact on our consolidated
	financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	January 2015, the FASB issued Accounting Standards Update 2015-01, "
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Income Statement&#151;Extraordinary and Unusual Items
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	". The
	provisions of this update simplify the income statement presentation requirements in Subtopic 225-20 by eliminating the concept of extraordinary items. Eliminating the extraordinary classification
	simplifies income statement presentation by altogether removing the concept of extraordinary items from consideration. We adopt this guidance from April&nbsp;1, 2016. The implementation of this
	standard is not expected to have a material effect on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	100
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_EC75001_1_101">
</A>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_BASECOLOR,"BLACK" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DEFAULTFONT,"FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLESHADECOLOR,"#CCEEFF" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_STABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:DOUBLE #000000 2.25PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_SCRTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID #000000 1.0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DCRTABLERULES,"BORDER-BOTTOM:DOUBLE #000000 2.25PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;" -->

</P>
<!-- TOC_END -->
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In September 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-16, "
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Business Combinations (Topic 805): Simplifying the Accounting for Measurement-Period
	Adjustments
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	". The amendments in this update require that an acquirer recognize adjustments to provisional amounts that are identified during the measurement period in the
	reporting period in which the adjustment amounts are determined. The update eliminates the current requirement to retrospectively adjust provisional amounts recognized at the acquisition date. The
	amendment is effective for us beginning April&nbsp;1, 2016. The implementation of this standard is not expected to have a material effect on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	November 2015, the FASB issued Accounting Standards Update 2015-17, "
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Income Taxes (Topic&nbsp;740): Balance Sheet Classification of Deferred
	Taxes
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	", which requires that deferred tax liabilities and assets be classified as noncurrent in a classified statement of financial position to simplify disclosure. The current
	requirement that deferred tax liabilities and assets of a tax-paying component of an entity be offset and presented as a single amount is not affected by the amendments in this update. The new
	standard will be effective for us beginning April&nbsp;1, 2016. The implementation of this standard is not expected to have a material effect on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	February 2016, the FASB issued Accounting Standards Update 2016-02, "
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Leases (Topic&nbsp;842)
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	". The purpose of this update is to
	increase transparency and comparability among organizations by requiring the recognition of lease assets and lease liabilities on the balance sheet. Most prominent among the amendments is the
	recognition of assets and liabilities by lessees for those leases classified as operating leases under previous U.S.&nbsp;GAAP. Under the new standard, disclosures are required to meet the objective
	of enabling users of financial statements to assess the amount, timing, and uncertainty of cash flows arising from leases. The amendment is effective for fiscal years beginning after
	December&nbsp;15, 2018, including interim reporting periods within those fiscal years. We are currently evaluating the impact of this accounting update on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_EC_5C">
</A>
	C.&nbsp;&nbsp;Research and Development, Patents and Licenses
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Research and development costs are expensed as incurred. The total amount of research and development activities was $6.7&nbsp;million, $3.2&nbsp;million and
	$2.9&nbsp;million for the years ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_EC_5D">
</A>
	D.&nbsp;&nbsp;Trend Information
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other than as disclosed elsewhere in this annual report, we are not aware of any trends, uncertainties, demands, commitments or events for the period from
	April&nbsp;1, 2015 to March&nbsp;31, 2016 that are reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on our net revenue, income, profitability, liquidity or capital resources, or that caused the
	disclosed financial information to be not necessarily indicative of future operating results or financial condition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_EC_5E">
</A>
	E.&nbsp;&nbsp;Off-Balance Sheet Arrangements
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not currently engage in off-balance sheet financing arrangements. In addition, we do not have any interest in entities referred to as variable interest
	entities, which includes special purposes entities and other structured finance entities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_EC_5F">
</A>
	F.&nbsp;&nbsp;Contractual Obligations
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The following table represents a summary of our estimated future payments under material contractual cash obligations as of March&nbsp;31, 2016. Changes in our
	business needs, cancellation
</FONT>
</P>

	101
</FONT>

<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=107,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=762261,FOLIO='102',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]EC75001A.;28',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;15:15' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_EC75001_1_103">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2228725Z20-F_HTM_BG75001A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Executive officers
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Dmitry Loshchinin&#151;Chief Executive Officer and President, Director
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Dmitry Loshchinin has served as our Chief Executive Officer since our inception in 2000. Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin also became a director
	of Luxoft in November of 2013. Prior to joining Luxoft, Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin served in management roles within software companies such as Kerntechnik, Entwicklung, Dinamyk&nbsp;GmbH (KED), Siemens
	Nixdorf Informationssysteme, AG (SNI) and IBM Corp. Beginning in 1998, he also oversaw IBS Group's initiative to offer offshore services. This initiative eventually became Luxoft.
	Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin holds a Master of Science degree in Applied Mathematics from Moscow State University and completed an executive education program at the Wharton School of the University of
	Pennsylvania.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Mikhail Friedland&#151;Executive Vice President
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mikhail Friedland has served as our Executive Vice President since 2006. Mr.&nbsp;Friedland leads Strategic Management and Continuous
	Improvement organization which consists of four units: (i)&nbsp;infrastructure, operation, security and internal automation, (ii)&nbsp;organizational transparency, analytics and controls, focusing
	on global and cross-functional processes, management frameworks and capacity, post-merger integration activities, (iii)&nbsp;continuous improvement, and (iv)&nbsp;M&amp;A. Mr.&nbsp;Friedland has
	more than 20&nbsp;years of experience in the IT and software services industry. Prior to joining Luxoft, Mr.&nbsp;Friedland worked as a software engineer for Merrill Lynch, Lehman Brothers and
	Merck (formerly Medco). In 1993, Mr.&nbsp;Friedland co-founded IT Consulting International ("ICTI"), which provided consulting and later outsourcing services for various U.S. clients. In 2006, we
	acquired ICTI. Mr.&nbsp;Friedland completed an executive education program at the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania and London Business School.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Roman Yakushkin&#151;Chief Financial Officer
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Roman Yakushkin has served as our Chief Financial Officer since 2006. In that role, Mr.&nbsp;Yakushkin leads the accounting and
	finance functions of our Company and is responsible for the quality of our consolidated financial statements prepared under U.S.&nbsp;GAAP. Mr.&nbsp;Yakushkin has over 15&nbsp;years of
	experience in budget management, financial management and business development. Prior to joining us, Mr.&nbsp;Yakushkin held several senior financial positions with a number of leading companies
	including Mobile Telesystems, FESCO and Louis Dreyfus. Mr.&nbsp;Yakushkin holds a Master of Business Administration degree from INSEAD and an undergraduate degree in Oriental Studies from Far
	Eastern State University. He is also a Chartered Financial Analyst.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Przemyslaw Berendt&#151;Vice President, Global Marketing
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Przemyslaw Berendt joined us as Managing Director for Poland in 2010, and has served as our Vice President of Global Marketing since
	April 2011. Mr.&nbsp;Berendt is responsible for our overall marketing strategy. Prior to joining us, Mr.&nbsp;Berendt served in the Global Business Services division of Procter&nbsp;&amp; Gamble,
	and as a branch manager of Betware, a midsize, international software development company. Mr.&nbsp;Berendt holds a Master of Science degree in Computer Science from DePaul University and a Bachelor

</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">

	Table of Contents

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	bonuses,
	stock-based compensation and directors' fees. This amount includes approximately $0.6&nbsp;million set aside or accrued to provide pension, severance, retirement or similar benefits or
	expenses. This amount does not include any professional and business association dues, business travel, relocation costs and other expenses and benefits commonly reimbursed or paid by companies in our
	industry and geographies.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We
	pay each of our three independent directors, Ms.&nbsp;Dyson and Messrs.&nbsp;Kasher and Pickering, an annual fee of $70,000. Each independent director receives an additional
	annual fee of $10,000 for his or her service on any Board committee, and a further annual fee of $10,000 for serving in the role of a Chairperson of any Board committee. We also reimburse our
	directors for reasonable and documented travel expenses incurred to attend board meetings. None of our directors is party to a service contract that provides for benefits upon the termination of the
	director's engagement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During
	the year ended March&nbsp;31, 2016, a total of 120,989 RSUs, 77,370 PSAs and 40,064 SARs have been vested into the ownership of our directors and executive officers under our
	Incentive Plan described below. Upon exercise of those instruments, 102,794 Class&nbsp;A ordinary shares have been issued.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Agreements with our Chief Executive Officer
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Second Amended and Restated Employment Agreement
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In November 2015, Mr.&nbsp;Dmitry Loshchinin, our President and CEO, entered into a Second Amended and Restated Employment Agreement,
	effective as of August&nbsp;12, 2014, with LGO. Under Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin's employment agreement, he has agreed to serve as our President and CEO. Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin also is a member of our
	board of directors. Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin's initial term of service under this agreement continues until August&nbsp;11, 2019. Thereafter, the agreement continues for successive one-year terms
	unless terminated by either party, generally by delivering six months' prior written notice on or before February&nbsp;11 of any year. Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin's salary and annual bonus are subject to
	review for increase at the discretion of our board of directors. Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin may also participate in certain executive benefit plans, in particular a pension plan established by LGO in
	accordance with the Swiss Federal Law on occupational pension schemes, as well as a loss of earnings insurance in case of illness, accident insurance and health insurance. We believe these are
	customary benefits made available to executive officers resident in Switzerland by employers of similar size operating in our industry. LGO currently pays 100% of the premium for all insurance
	coverages listed above.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If
	Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin's employment is terminated (i)&nbsp;by us without cause (as defined in the employment agreement and described below), (ii)&nbsp;by Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin with
	good reason (as defined in the employment agreement, and which includes a material reduction in his base salary or bonus, a material reduction in his title, duties and authority or a material adverse
	change in the reporting structure, LGO's material
	breach of the employment agreement or our material breach of the RSU agreement (described below), or our failure or LGO's failure to obtain assumption of the employment agreement by a successor), in
	each case of (i)&nbsp;and (ii)&nbsp;whether or not in connection with a change in control, or (iii)&nbsp;due to disability or death, he or his designated beneficiary or estate administrator, as
	applicable, is entitled to receive: (1)&nbsp;accrued salary and accrued but unused vacation through the termination date, (2)&nbsp;any earned but unpaid annual bonus for our completed fiscal year
	immediately preceding the termination date, pro-rated through the termination date, (3)&nbsp;a payment equal to twelve months of his then base salary, payable over the twelve-month period following
	the termination date, and (4)&nbsp;the continuation of life, accident and health insurance coverage in the same scope as covering Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin and his family immediately prior to
	termination date, for eighteen months following the termination date. Additionally, the unvested portion of Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin's RSU award (as described below) will immediately vest pro-rated based
	upon the portion of the period of restriction (as defined in the RSU agreement) that Mr.&nbsp;Loshchinin was employed prior to the date of termination, and all
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	107
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=7,SEQ=112,EFW="2228725",CP="LUXOFT HOLDING INC",DN="1",CHK=612772,FOLIO='107',FILE='DISK122:[16ZBJ1.16ZBJ75001]EC75001A.;28',USER='CHE106816',CD='29-JUL-2016;15:15' -->
<A NAME="A2228725Z20-F_HTM_PAGE_EC75001_1_108">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
